Motivation

The boss told us …

  1. We have millions of SNPs. We need to do GWAS discovering new loci!
    • Look. For sure, we will get ultra-fashioned new loci and publish the articles.
    • Why? We have hundreds of phenotypes! It is just like a lottery.
  2. Diseases are the most important phenotypes!
    • GAIT2 has records of CVI (a fashion phenotype).

Proposed analysis

Workflow 0: data preparation

  1. Prepare phenotypes
    • 81 traits: inormal transformation + AGE/SEX covariates (04-assoc-mapping3-MatrixLmer)
    • 21 traits: outlier detection + exclusion criteria + custom transformation + AGE/AGE2/SEX covariates (05-assoc-mapping4-MatrixLmer)
  2. Prepare genotypes
    • A mix of data formats: NCDF from GWASTools + genocov by SOLAR, split into batches
    • The last version of filters: MAF >= 0.01, info >= 0.3 (Verma et al. 2014)
    • 18,208,087 imputed and missing annotation, annotation.md:
      • 440,948 after IMPUTE2 (hg19)
      • 108,846 after 1K (hg19)
      • 46,054 after 1K + UCSC (hg19, snpDB 142)

Workflow 1: MatrixEQTL + lme4/SOLAR

  1. Estimate polygenic model and get the covariance matrix
  2. Run MatrixEQTL in parallel (M = 10M)
  3. Apply pvOutputThreshold = 1e-3 (1e-4 in the first mappings 2-3)
  4. Run lme4 in parallel (M = 100K-300K)

Source: 17-run-assoc-mapping4.R

Workflow 2: GLOGS + SOLAR

GLOGS is a genome-wide logistic mixed model/score test (Stanhope & Abney, 2012)

  1. Estimate GLOGS polygenic model (a random sample or cubature for L(theta))
  2. Run GLOGS association score-based model in parallel (M = 10M).
  3. Apply p-value threshold 1e-3.
  4. Run SOLAR in parallel (M = 100K-200K)

Source: 01-run-polygenic.R & 02-run-assoc.R

Conclusions

Things we’ve learned from GWAS in GAIT2

  • MatrixEQTL requires a special tunning for related individuals
    • Passing kinship matrix doesn’t work
    • Regressing out covariates doesn’t work
    • Solution: variance-covariance matrix from the polygenic model
  • Power of GWAS in GAIT2 is similar to that in GAIT1
    • <1,000 individuals leads to detection of only large-effect loci
    • GWAS is dead?

Other QTL mappings we’ve done

# GAIT data
library(gait)
phen <- gait2.phen(id.alert = TRUE, transforms = "tr1")
kin2 <- solarKinship2(phen)
snpfiles <- gait1.snpfiles()

# Multi-variate assoc.
library(solarius)
A <- solarPolyAssoc(tr1_PSfree + tr1_PSfunc ~ 1, phen, mga.files = snpfiles, cores = 64)

# Gene-based post-gwas assoc.
library(vegas)
G <- vegas(A$snpf, genesize = 10, chr = 1, cores = 64)

# PG x Discrete var.
library(solaris)
M <- relmatLmer(tr1_PSfree ~ 1 + (0 + SEX|ID), phen, relmat = list(ID = kin2))

# PG x Cont. var.
M <- relmatLmer(tr1_PSfree ~ 1 + (AGE|ID), phen, relmat = list(ID = kin2))

# Linkage MGxE
M <- relmatLmer(tr1_PSfree ~ 1 + (AGE|ID) + (AGE|IBDID), phen, relmat = list(ID = kin2, IBDID = ibd))

Tested ideas that failed/worked partially

  • gene-based test by VEGAS2: not powerful by itselft & more SNPs are needed
  • pathway-based: the first try could not work > need experts
  • multi-trait GWAS: no results for the traits in Coagulation Cascade
  • metaphen v2: no one had time to go further the first graphical result
  • ibd estimation: go further the Alfonso’s proposal of LD prunning & found IBDLD
  • sex-specificity by SOLAR: found the bug in the GAIT1 case study of mtDNA

Things to do

  • Phen. revision
    • apply exclusion criteria (e.g. Souto’s note)
    • include more traits & add more covariates, e.g. diet, physical activity
    • impute phen. based on polygenic model
  • Score-based GWAS v2 (similar to modern GWAS tools, e.g. )
    • re-define MAF (based on MAC) & imputation score (e.g. 0.9)
    • estimate the correction constant based on ~ 100 random SNPs
    • save all SNPs for gene- and pathway-based follow up
    • Add X/MT Chromosomes
  • Genome-wide scans
    • GWHA to detect rare loci
    • GWL
      • bivariate
      • GxE & Parent-of-origin
